lc 912 , problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/sort-an-array/description/
Approach: Merge Sort (Divide and Conquer)
Intuition
A single element is already sorted. We can recursively divide the array into two halves until each subarray contains only one element. Then, while returning from the recursion, we merge the sorted halves into a single sorted array.

The key idea is that merging two sorted arrays can be done efficiently using two pointers.

Algorithm
If the array contains one or zero elements, return it as it is already sorted.

Divide the array into two halves.

Recursively sort the left half.

Recursively sort the right half.

Merge the two sorted halves using two pointers:

Compare the current elements of both halves.
Append the smaller element to the result array.
Once one half is exhausted, append all remaining elements from the other half.
Return the merged sorted array.

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity: O(n log n)

The array is divided into two halves at each recursive level, giving log n levels.
At every level, all n elements are merged exactly once.
Therefore, the total time complexity is O(n log n).
Space Complexity: O(n)

An auxiliary array is used during the merge step.
The recursion stack contributes an additional O(log n) space, but the overall auxiliary space is O(n).
Python Code
class Solution:
    def sortArray(self, nums: List[int]) -> List[int]:
        def merge_array(left, right):
            result = []
            i, j = 0, 0
            n, m = len(left), len(right)

            while i < n and j < m:
                if left[i] <= right[j]:
                    result.append(left[i])
                    i += 1
                else:
                    result.append(right[j])
                    j += 1

            while i < n:
                result.append(left[i])
                i += 1

            while j < m:
                result.append(right[j])
                j += 1

            return result

        def merge_sort(arr):
            if len(arr) <= 1:
                return arr

            mid = len(arr) // 2
            left = merge_sort(arr[:mid])
            right = merge_sort(arr[mid:])

            return merge_array(left, right)

        return merge_sort(nums)
